# Command newest-file

## What does this command do:

Locates and display the newest file name and date in the path of the current directory structure

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: cd ~/tools && git pull
For Raspberry Pi install using: cd ~/tools && git pull
For Mac install using: cd ~/tools && git pull

## Command path

For Fedora run: ~/tools/newest-file
For Raspberry Pi run: ~/tools/newest-file
For Mac run: ~/tools/newest-file

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://github.com/kevinpinscoe/tools/blob/main/newest-file

## Command options

newest-file          # run from any directory; no flags

Output format:
  <relative/path/to/file>  YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS

Notes:
  - Skips hidden paths (.git, .terraform, etc.)
  - Searches recursively from the current directory
  - Requires python3
